\f0\i0\b \cf0 \
Preliminaries:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 TeXShop is a Mac OS X program which can typeset TeX and Latex files and preview the output on the screen. The program typesets using 
\f1\i pdftex
\f2\i0  or 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  instead of 
\f1\i tex
\f2\i0  or 
\f1\i latex
\f2\i0 ; these programs output pdf files rather than dvi files. Since pdf is the native graphics format of Mac OS X, it is easy to display the output on the screen. 
\f1\i Pdftex
\f2\i0  and 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  were written by  Han The Thanh, Petr Sojka, and Jiri Zlatuska.\
\
The pdf files created by TeXShop are standard pdf files which can be given to other people and displayed on a variety of computer systems. For example, they can be displayed by Adobe Acrobat on Mac OS 9. \
\
TeXShop does not include TeX. Instead it uses the standard TeX distribution 
\f1\i teTeX
\f2\i0 , a wonderful collection of the entire suite of TeX programs, files, and utilities created by Thomas Esser. This collection (the standard version of TeX on Linux systems) has been compiled for Mac OS X. Instructions for obtaining it are given below.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Getting and Installing teTeX:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 Gerben Wierda has compiled the latest teTeX for MacOSX. His version is on the website\
\
	http://www.uoregon.edu/~koch/texshop/texshop.html\
\
and at\
\
	ftp://ftp.nluug.nl/pub/comp/next/MacOSX/teTeX-1.07-fmt-1.02.macosx.tar.gz\
\
The file at the Oregon site is named "tetex.tar.gz" and the file in The Netherlands is named "teTeX-1.07-fmt-1.02.macosx.tar.gz". Obtain one of these files and place it in your home directory. Open a terminal and type the following commands, one after another:\
\
                
\f3\fs20 cd\
        sudo  tcsh\
        tar  -zpPxvf  tetex.tar.gz\
        cd  /usr/local\
        mkdir  bin\
        cd  /usr/local/teTeX\
        source  mklinks\

\f2\fs24                \
 If your printer uses letter size paper rather than A4 size paper, as is likely in the US, issue the command\
 \
                
\f3\fs20 texconfig  dvips  paper  letter\

\f2\fs24                \
These commands must be issued from an Administrator account. The account created when Mac OS X was installed is such an account. The "sudo" command will issue a warning and ask for a password; give your regular user password. The "tar" command will produce a large number of output lines, including warning lines with the message "unable to set uid/guid; no such file or directory." This is normal; ignore the warnings. When you are done, quit the Terminal program. You can throw the file "tetex.tar.gz" away.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Getting and Installing TeXShop:
\f2\b0 \
\
In your user account, log onto the following web site:\
\
	www.uoregon.edu/~koch/texshop/texshop.html\
\
Click the link ``TeXShop Program''. This will produce a file titled texshop.tar.gz. In a terminal program, type the following commands:\
\
                
\f3\fs20 gzip  -d  texshop.tar.gz\
        tar  -xf  texshop.tar\
        rm  texshop.tar.gz
\f2\fs24 \
\
This will produce a folder titled ``TeXShop Folder.'' The TeXShop Folder contains TeXShop and several files which can be read or discarded. Drag TeXShop to the Applications folder. If you intend to use it often, drag its icon to the Dock.\
\

\f0\b Typesetting Documents:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 To use TeXShop, type your Latex input in the editing window it provides. Then push the "Latex" button at the top of the window. The input will be saved and 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  will run. A second window will open displaying messages from 
\f1\i tex
\f2\i0 . If there are errors, 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  will halt; type "return" to skip the errors one by one, or one of the standard tex inputs to quit, run continuously, etc. After the document has been typeset, a new window will appear showing the resulting pdf file.\
\
To typeset a TeX document, push the "Program" button and select TeX instead of Latex. If you usually use TeX, choose it as your default program in the Preferences Dialog.\
\
If you notice an error, you can immediately fix it in the editing window and push the "TeX" or "Latex" button again without halting the first invocation of 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0 . The program will kill that invocation and run another. \
\
TeXShop remembers the source lines of the first twenty errors. To cycle through these lines in the source file, choose "Go To Error" in the Edit menu or type the keyboard shortcut for this menu item.\
\
When you fix errors and typeset again, the viewer will remember the page you were previously viewing.\
\
If a line in the source begins with the characters "%:", TeXShop interprets the remaining word or words on the line as a "tag" and adds these words to the Tag pulldown menu. Choosing a tag entry in this menu will scroll to the appropriate line in the source file. \
\
TeXShop can show handle multiple documents. If you choose "New" or "Open,"  your original document will remain and additional windows for the new document will open. If you open a tex file in a folder which contains a pdf file with the same name, this pdf will also appear.\
\
You can start TeXShop by double clicking on a document with extension ".tex". The program will open that input document and (if it exists) the associated pdf document.\
\
You can close the pdf window at any time. It will reappear when the document is typeset again. If you close the input window then both the input and output windows will close (windows from other tex documents will remain open). Therefore, if an input source window is cluttering the screen, hide it instead of closing it.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f1\i \cf0 Warning: pdftex
\f2\i0  and 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  are unix programs which do not like spaces in filenames. Source files created with TeXShop should be given names without spaces. TeXShop itself has no problem with spaces in filenames.  \
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Including Graphics:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 It is common to use eps (encapsulated postscript) graphic files in TeX documents because such files print well at any size. The native graphics format of Mac OS X is pdf (postscript display format); these files also print well at any size. Consequently, graphics for TeXShop documents should be created in pdf format. It is likely that most Mac graphics programs will be modified to output pdf over the next few months. Utilities are beginning to appear which can convert from one graphic format to another. Please consult the standard archives.\
\
The authors of 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0  have made it easy to include graphic files in a Latex document typeset with 
\f1\i pedlatex
\f2\i0 , even if the document will later be typeset by standard 
\f1\i latex
\f2\i0  and converted to a dvi file for distribution to other people. At the top of such a Latex input file, include the following lines:\
\
	
\f3\fs20 \\newif\\ifpdf\
	\\ifx\\pdfoutput\\undefined\
	\\pdffalse % we are not running PDFLaTeX\
	\\else\
	\\pdfoutput=1 % we are running PDFLaTeX\
	\\pdftrue\
	\\fi\
\
	\\ifpdf\
	\\usepackage[pdftex]\{graphicx\}\
	\\else\
	\\usepackage\{graphicx\}\
	\\fi\

\f2\fs24  
\f0\b \

\f2\b0 After the "\\begin\{document\}" command, include the lines\
\
	
\f3\fs20 \\ifpdf\
	\\DeclareGraphicsExtensions\{.pdf, .jpg\}\
	\\else\
	\\DeclareGraphicsExtensions\{.eps, .jpg\}\
	\\fi\
\

\f2\fs24 When you wish to include a graphic file, say "f1.pdf ", use the command\
\
	
\f3\fs20 \\includegraphics[width=2in]\{f1\}
\f2\fs24 \
\
This command will cause 
\f1\i tex
\f2\i0  to input the graphic file "f1.pdf" when the text is typeset with 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0 , but input the file "f1.eps" when the text is typeset with 
\f1\i latex.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\i0\b \cf0 Modifying the Templates Menu:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 When TeXShop runs for the first time, it creates a folder\
\
	~/Library/TeXShop/Templates\
\
and places the files 
\f1\i Graphics.tex, TexTemplate.tex,
\f2\i0  and 
\f1\i LatexTemplate.tex
\f2\i0  in this folder. The names of these files are shown under the Templates pull down menu at the top of the input window. Choosing one of these items inserts the contents of the template file at the current cursor position in the source.\
\
The three template files are standard tex files which can be opened and edited by TeXShop. Additional tex files can be inserted into the Templates folder; they will also appear under the Templates pull down menu provided their names end with the extension ".tex". The original template files can be removed if desired.\
\
To restore the original template files after they have been edited, delete the Templates folder and run TeXShop again. It will recreate the folder and restore its original contents.  
\f0\b \
\
Setting a Project Root File:\
\

\f2\b0 It is common to split large input files into several smaller files controlled by a 
\f1\i root
\f2\i0  file. For instance, the root file of a book project might have the form\
\
	
\f3\fs20 \\documentclass[11pt]\{book\}\
	\\includeonly\{Chapter2/two.tex\}\
	\\textwidth = 6.5 in\
	\\textheight = 9 in\
	\\begin\{document\}\
	\\include\{Chapter1/one.tex\}\
	\\include\{Chapter2/two.tex\}\
	\\include\{Chapter3/three.tex\}\
	\\end\{document\}\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 	\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 This root file contains formatting commands for the entire project, but the subject matter is contained in files 
\f1\i one.tex, two.tex,
\f2\i0  and 
\f1\i three.tex
\f2\i0 . The second line above tells TeX to typeset chapter two only, speeding up typesetting while chapter two is being written. When the book is complete, this line can be commented out and the entire book can be typeset a final time.\
\
While chapter two is being written, it would be natural to open the file 
\f1\i two.tex
\f2\i0  in TeXShop. But after changes are made to this input file, TeXShop should not typeset 
\f1\i two.tex
\f2\i0 ; instead it should typeset the root file. TeXShop can be told to do so using the menu command "Set Project Root..."  This menu command presents a panel with a text box where the name of the root file can be entered. \
\
If the root file is in the same folder as the input file, it is enough to give its name, including the ".tex" extension. For instance, if the root file is named 
\f1\i Main
\f2\i0 , you can enter 
\f1\i Main.tex
\f2\i0  in the dialog window.\
\
If the root file is in a different directory, its name can be given relative to the location of the input file. In the above example, the various chapters are contained in subfolders within the folder containing the root file. In that case, you could enter 
\f1\i ../Main.tex
\f2\i0  in the dialog window, showing the location of the root file relative to the chapter input file.\
\
Finally, the name of the root can be given with an absolute name, as in 
\f1\i /Users/me/Main.tex
\f2\i0 .\
\
If the entire TeX source is contained in a single file, it is not necessary to set the root project name.\
\
TeXShop remembers the name of the root file by writing this information to a file with the same name as the input file and the extension ".texshop". For instance, if the input for chapter two is in 
\f1\i two.tex
\f2\i0 , TeXShop writes the name of the root in 
\f1\i two.texshop
\f2\i0  in the same directory as 
\f1\i two.tex
\f2\i0 .  If the file 
\f1\i two.texshop
\f2\i0  is later thrown away, TeXShop will revert to typesetting 
\f1\i two.tex
\f2\i0  rather than 
\f1\i Main.tex
\f2\i0 . \
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

