\f0\b \cf0 Printing:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 To print a Tex output file, select the "Print" menu item. To print Tex source, select the "Print Source" menu item.\
\
Printing can also be done directly within teTeX without using TeXShop. When you want to print, open a terminal window and typeset your document a final time with 
\f1\i tex
\f2\i0  or 
\f1\i latex
\f2\i0  rather than 
\f1\i pdftex
\f2\i0  or 
\f1\i pdflatex
\f2\i0 , for instance by using the command\
\
	latex myfile\
\
This will yield a dvi file. Print the dvi file using the command\
\
	dvips myfile\
\
There are two problems with this method. First, it only works if you have a postscript printer. Tex experts may know how to get around this problem. Second, even after you define a printer with the Print Center application, it isn't known to the lpr daemon, so dvips will complain that there is no printer available. Mike Najarian posted a note about lpr printing on the macosx-admin mailing list maintained by Omnigroup.  Here are Najarian's instructions:\
\
1) Using a text editor, create a file called "myprintcap" with text similar to the following. The entry "My_Printer" at the start can be any name you choose to call the printer within Mac OS X. The entry  "host.domain.edu" should be replaced with the tcp/ip address of your printer, or the tcp/ip address of the computer which is hosting your printer. The entry "HPLaserJet" should be replaced with the name of your printer on the hosting machine. The second two lines of this file begin with tabs.\
\
My_Printer: \\\
	:lp=:rm=host.domain.edu:rp=HPLaserJet:sd=/var/spool/lpd/HPLaserJet: \\\
	:ty=PostScript:\
\
Be sure to save the file in straight text form rather than in rtf form. If your printer is directly connected rather than remotely over ethernet, I don't know what these entries should be.\
\
2) Start up Terminal. Enter the command\
\
	sudo niload printcap  /  <  myprintcap\
\
3) Create the folder /var/spool/lpd/HPLaserJet, replacing "HPLaserJet" with the printer name you entered earlier.\
\
4) Start the PrinterCenter app. It will see the new printer created in netinfo. Click to accept the choice and the new printer will become your default printer.\
\
5) Using an editor, create a text file in your home directory named ".cshrc" with contents\
\
	setenv PRINTER My_Printer\
\
replacing "My_Printer" with the name you selected earlier.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 BibTeX:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 BibTeX is a tool used to create bibliographies in Latex documents. The tool assumes that you have a large database of references which you often quote. Simple commands allow you to cite certain of these references in your latex source, and BibTeX then creates a bibliography for your article containing only the items cited. \
\
Here is a brief example taken from 
\f1\i The Latex Companion
\f2\i0  by Goossens, Mittelbach, and Samarin. Consult this book for many additional details.  Suppose the database is a file called "mybibliography.bib" containing the text shown below. In this text, the entries "Felici:1991, Knuth:WEB," and "Liang:1983" are key values used to cite the articles in the latex source.\
	\
	@article\{Felici:1991,\
	author	=\{James Felici\},\
	title	=\{\{PostScript versus TrueType\}\},\
	journal	=\{Macworld\},\
	volume	=8, pages=\{195--201\},\
	month	=sep, year = 1991		\}\
\
	@techreport\{Knuth:WEB,\
	title	=\{\{The \\textsf\{WEB\} System of\
		Structured Documentation\}\},\
	month	=sep, year = 1983,\
	author	=\{Donald E. Knuth\},\
	address	=\{Stanford, CA 94305\},\
	number	=\{STAN-CS-83-980\},\
	institution=\{Department of Computer\
		Science, Stanford University\}  \}\
\
	@phdthesis\{Liang:1983,\
	author	=\{Franklin Mark Liang\},\
	month	=jun, year = 1983,\
	school	=\{Stanford University\},\
	address	=\{Stanford, CA 94305\},\
	title	=\{\{Word Hy-phen-a-tion by\
		Com-pu-ter\}\},\
	note	=\{Also available as Stanford\
		University, Department of\
		Computer Science Report\
		No. STAN-CS-83-977\}   \}\
\
\
Suppose the latex source file is called "myfile.tex" and contains the following text:\
\
	\\begin\{document\}\
	Consider the  argument of Felici~\\cite\{Felici:1991\} in light of these comments.\
	\\nocite\{Liang:1983\} We provide further remarks later.\
\
	\\bibliographystyle\{plain\}\
	\\bibliography\{mybibliography\}\
	\\end\{document\}\
\
When this source is typeset, a reference to Felici's article will appear in the text, and a bibliography will be created at the end of the text containing the articles of Felici and Liang, but not the article of Knuth.\
\
TeXShop can be used with this example in the following way. First edit and typeset the document "myfile.tex" as usual. Citations will appear in the output as "[?]" and the bibliography will be missing. Then select "Bibtex" under the Program button and run Bibtex. Next select "Latex" and typeset again. Citations will still appear as "[?]", but the bibliography will be added to the output. Typeset a final time, and citations will have their correct values.\
\
The file "mybibliography.bib" can be opened and edited by TeXShop. When TeXShop opens a file whose name does not end with the extension ".tex" or ".TEX", it dims the typesetting buttons. When the file is later saved using "Save" or "Save As ...", the file will be saved with exactly the selected name, without adding a  ".tex" extension to the name. So items can be added to the bibliography database at the same time that a new article is being written.\
\
(However, if you use TeXShop to create the file "mybibliography.bib" in the first place, it will have a ".tex"  extension when saved. This is a bug we hope to fix eventually. Remove the ".tex" in the Finder and open the file again to continue editing.)\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 MakeIndex:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 MakeIndex is a tool used to add an index to a LaTeX document. To create such an index, you should\
\
	a) Add the command "\\usepackage\{makeidx\}" to the top of the source file\
        \
        	b) Put a "\\makeindex" command in the document preamble\
                \
               c) Put a "\\printindex" command where the index should appear, often just before "\\end\{document\}"\
               \
               d) Put index references in the source document, as in the example below:\
               \
               "There are many animals in the world \\index\{animal\}. Examples include bears and tigers \\index\{bear|tiger\}\
               and various insects \\index\{insect|see\{animal\}\}."\
               \
 To create the index, typeset the document as usual. Then run MakeIndex. Then typeset again.\
 \
 Many additional details can be found in 
\f1\i The Latex Companion
\f2\i0  by Goossens, Mittelbach, and Samarin.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Opening Other Files with TeXShop:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 TeXShop can open most files for editing. This facility has been provided so users can read TeX-related files with extensions ".log", ".aux", etc. Files with extensions ".jpg", ".tiff", and ".pdf" are opened as graphic files.\
\
However, it is not a good idea to use TeXShop as a general editor. TeXShop can read files written in UniCode and other formats, but it always saves files in 8-bit Ascii format because that is the format which 
\f1\i tex
\f2\i0  and 
\f1\i latex
\f2\i0  understand. Consequently, information may be lost if TeXShop is used to edit files which really aren't related to TeX.  
\f0\b \

\f2\b0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Graphic Conversions:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 TeX graphic files are often created as eps or tiff files. These files must be converted to pdf or jpg for screen viewing, and to eps for printing with dvips. \
\
	1) There is a utility called ``epstopdf'' in ghostscript which can convert \
	from eps to pdf. To create the file "mygraphics.pdf" from "mygraphics.eps",\
